process.nextTick is a native module. You can test this simply yourself:<p><pre><code>    var a = 1;
    process.nextTick(function() {
      console.log(a);
    });
    a = 2;</code></pre>

Refactoring is fun, especially on a slow day. The &quot;Introducing an Explaining Variable&quot;[1] refactoring is:<p><pre><code>  if (version < 8 && ua ~ &quot;IE&quot;) ...
</code></pre>
is better written as<p><pre><code>  IE8 = (version < 8 && ua ~ &quot;IE&quot;);
  if (IE8) ...
</code></pre>
This allows variable IE8 to be (1) reused later on in the code, (2) is self documenting and (3) sets a precedent for extending it easily by future devs:<p><pre><code>  IE8 = (version < 8 && ua ~= &quot;IE&quot;);
  mobile = (ua ~= &quot;mobile&quot;)
  if (IE8 || mobile) ...

</code></pre>
Another quick one is Guard Clauses[2].<p><pre><code>  function {
    if (...) {
      ...
    } else {
      ...
    }
  }
</code></pre>
where either block is long, is better written as<p><pre><code>  function {
    if (...) {
      return ...;
    }
    ...
  }
</code></pre>
This site <a href="http://sourcemaking.com/refactoring" rel="nofollow">http://sourcemaking.com/refactoring</a> is worth a read even if you have been programming for years; especially if you have been programming for years and haven&#x27;t developed good habits.<p><pre><code>  [1] http://sourcemaking.com/refactoring/introduce-explaining-variable
  [2] http://sourcemaking.com/refactoring/replace-nested-conditional-with-guard-clauses</code></pre>
